    Create a Java program consisting of two classes: Student and StudentMain.

       Student Class:

       Define a class named Student with the following instance variables:
       sName: representing the name of the student (String).
       sAddress: representing the address of the student (String).
       rollNo: representing the roll number of the student (int).
       age: representing the age of the student (int).
       Implement a constructor Student(String sName, String sAddress, int rollNo, int age) to initialize the instance variables.
       Provide getter and setter methods for each instance variable to facilitate access and modification.
       Override the toString() method to return a string representation of the Student object.
       StudentMain Class:

       Define a class named StudentMain with a main method as the program's entry point.
       Inside the main method, prompt the user to input the number of Student objects to create.
       Create an array student[] of Student objects based on the user input.
       Prompt the user to input details (roll number, name, age, and address) for each student and populate the student[] array.
       Create another array result[] to store Student objects meeting specific criteria (age >= 18 and address is "Hyderabad").
       Iterate through the student[] array and filter out Student objects meeting the criteria, storing them in the result[] array.
       Display the filtered Student objects stored in the result[] array to the user as the program's output.


